What is JSX?
Simple Definition
JSX (JavaScript XML) is a syntax extension for JavaScript that lets you write HTML-like code inside JavaScript.

Why JSX?

Without JSX, React code becomes harder to read because you need to use React.createElement().

Without JSX:
const element = React.createElement(
    "h1",
    null,
    "Hello, World!"
);

With JSX:
const element = <h1>Hello, World!</h1>;
JSX is much cleaner and easier to understand.
✅ Is converted into JavaScript by tools like Babel before running in the browser.


Example:
const name = "John";
function App() {
    return <h1>Hello, {name}!</h1>;
}
Output:
Hello, John!


JSX Rules
1..Return a single parent element.
✔ Correct:
return (
<div>
<h1>Hello</h1>
<p>Welcome</p>
</div>
);

❌ Incorrect:
return (
<h1>Hello</h1>
<p>Welcome</p>
);



 2..Close all tags.
✔ Correct:
<img src="image.png" />
<br />
<input />



3..Use className instead of class.
<div className="container">
    Hello
</div>


4..Use camelCase for attributes.
Examples:
onClick
tabIndex
htmlFor
autoFocus

Interview Answer
JSX (JavaScript XML) is a syntax extension for JavaScript that allows developers to write HTML-like code inside JavaScript.
It makes React code more readable and is transpiled into JavaScript using Babel before execution.

